name: NPR
text:
An NPR report revealed the Trump administration awarded over $6 billion in vaccine contracts through a third party. Government contracts executed this way aren't required to include taxpayer protections. 

Now, it faces calls to disclose those contracts. https://t.co/FHEOk5iPSE

name: NPR
text: As politicians prepare for the possibility of a contested election, Gen. Mark Milley, the chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, says the military "will obey the lawful orders of civilian control." https://t.co/RMTGMWMznP

name: NPR
text:
Despite the new stresses, women are drawing upon their inner strength to survive — and even thrive. "Women are responding in the ways that they often do: with an incredible display of resilience."

Here are the stories of 19 women around the world: https://t.co/4e6aWonrST

name: NPR
text:
Estée Lauder is reportedly paying $17,500 an hour to have astronauts take photos and videos of its skincare serum in space. NASA has set aside 90 hours of crew time for commercial and marketing activities like this.  
https://t.co/82Q7E6eZOm

name: NPR
text:
Graciela Iturbide has spent half a century capturing the beauty of her homeland — and calling for Mexico to reclaim its sense of pride and identity.

"There is no need to pursue the American dream," the photographer says. "We have our own here, too." https://t.co/jrrJOudKvQ

name: NPR
text:
Outdoor learning holds promise beyond limiting the spread of COVID-19, according to longtime practitioners. The curiosity and connection sparked by it could be a much-needed antidote to the anxiety and stress of 2020. @MindShiftKQED
https://t.co/4D4lVtVc5I

name: NPR
text:
How about some good news?

These teen girls won an international competition for developing an app that helps patients with dementia.
https://t.co/N4Jgu8EL8U

text: Auctions are at the heart of this year's Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Scientists. The winners, Stanford University professors Paul Milgrom and Robert Wilson were recognized "for improvements to auction theory and inventions of new auction formats."  https://t.co/bBXj8lWhjZ

name: NPR
text: The Glass Fire in Northern California has forced thousands of people from their homes. Among them, residents of Santa Rosa's first government-funded homeless camp, who are now displaced again. https://t.co/HKaY6d46k2

text: RT @NPRinskeep: "The Senate is doing its duty constitutionally," begins committee chairman Graham, who had publicly said on video that he would never try to confirm a justice in an election year, as he is now doing. "Our Democratic friends" will "have a chance to have their say.""The Senate is doing its duty constitutionally," begins committee chairman Graham, who had publicly said on video t… https://t.co/dyFAQcPiEc

name: NPR
text:
RT @nprpolitics: In 2016, GOP Sen. Lindsey Graham said a Supreme Court vacancy shouldn't be filled during an election year, adding "use my words against me."

Now, he's changed his position and is pushing forward with Amy Coney Barrett's confirmation. https://t.co/uGtIjXBcNZ

name: NPR
text:
The Senate Judiciary Committee begins up to four days of hearings Monday on President Trump's nomination of Amy Coney Barrett to the U.S. Supreme Court.

If confirmed, Barrett, 48, would replace the late Ruth Bader Ginsburg on the high court. https://t.co/KyojyaRRbv

name: NPR
text: Physicians are starting to see the effects of a warming planet in the exam room, now medical residents are being educated on how to speak and write publicly about the intersection of health and climate change. https://t.co/VeDMdW1ZY5

name: NPR
text: RT @nprpolitics: GOP Sen. Mike Lee, who tested positive for the coronavirus just 10 days ago, is in attendance at the confirmation hearings for Amy Coney Barrett — and delivered his opening statement without wearing a mask. https://t.co/2FsrK3ukFo

name: NPR
text:
Utah Republican Sen. Mike Lee, who tested positive for coronavirus following a White House event for Supreme Court nominee Amy Coney Barrett, returned to the Capitol on Monday.

It was unclear if Lee had tested negative for the illness before attending. https://t.co/JHjuAZp7fZ

name: NPR
text:
Senate Judiciary Committee Chairman Lindsey Graham, R-S.C., will preside over the hearings, which are expected to last four days. 

The panel is expected to vote on Oct. 22, which will be followed by a floor vote by the end of the month. https://t.co/DuD8qMq9Kb

name: NPR
text: Democrats blasted efforts to move forward with Amy Coney Barrett's nomination so close to Election Day in Monday's hearing. "There's nothing unconstitutional about this process," Republicans argued. https://t.co/DIPNtCmuZx

name: NPR
text: The confirmation hearings for Judge Amy Coney Barrett begin today, amid a pandemic and against the backdrop of early voting that has begun in many states and just 22 days before Election. https://t.co/HUFG4dO3jB
